1) WAP to find and print the unit digit of a number stored in a variable.
Code:
public class Test {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        int x=5456;
        System.out.println("Unit digit is "+x%10);
    }
}

2) WAP to print the number stored in a variable without it's last digit.
Code:
public class Test {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        int x=5456;
        System.out.println("Unit digit is "+x/10);
    }
}

3) WAP to swap two int variables.
Code:
public class Test {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        int x=10,y=20,z;
        System.out.println("x="+x+" y="+y);
        z=x;
        x=y;
        y=z;
        System.out.println("x="+x+" y="+y);
    }
}

4) WAP to swap two int variables without using a third variable.
Code:
public class Test {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        int x=10,y=20;
        System.out.println("x="+x+" y="+y);
        x=x^y;
        y=x^y;
        x=x^y;
        System.out.println("x="+x+" y="+y);
    }
}

5) How to identify whether a variable is value type variable or nullable type?
Ans:
Primitive types are value type variables while non primitive types can be nullable or non-nullable.
Only reference variables can hold null value, hence reference variables are nullable types and
value types cannot hold null value.
If we add [] after a primitive type then it is a reference variable.

6) Why there's a error in java statement - float x=3.5;
Ans:
Because value assigned to the variable 'x' is of double data type. 
But variable is capable of holding a float data type. To assign 
float value to the variable, use - float x=3.5f;

7) What's the result of expression - 35&83?
Ans:

35 & 83 = 3

8) What's the result of expression 47|29?
Ans:

47 | 29 = 63

9) What's the result of expression 76^108?
Ans:

76 ^ 108 = 32

10) WAP to rotate digits of a number towards right by one position.
Code:
public class Test {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        int a,x=5667;
        System.out.println(x);
        a=x%10;
        x=x/10;
        System.out.println(""+a+x);
    }
}
